/**
 * Azure AD (Entra ID) - Resource Owner Password Credentials (ROPC) Flow POC
 * ----------------------------------------------------------------------
 * Demonstrates acquiring an access token directly from a username/password
 * using the OAuth2 "password" grant against Azure AD's v2.0 token endpoint.
 *
 * IMPORTANT LIMITATIONS (read before using this anywhere near production):
 * - ROPC does NOT work if the user account has MFA enabled, is a guest/B2B
 *   account, uses federated auth (ADFS), or requires Conditional Access
 *   satisfaction (device compliance, sign-in risk, etc.) — the request
 *   will simply fail.
 * - Microsoft explicitly discourages ROPC. It bypasses the interactive
 *   sign-in UI entirely, which means your app becomes responsible for
 *   handling the user's raw password. There's no support for passwordless,
 *   FIDO2, smart card, or SSO scenarios.
 * - Personal Microsoft accounts (outlook.com/live.com/hotmail.com) are not
 *   supported at all — only work/school (Azure AD) accounts.
 * - Use only for POC/testing/legacy migration scenarios, or for daemon-like
 *   automation against dedicated non-interactive test accounts. For real
 *   apps, use Authorization Code + PKCE (interactive) via MSAL instead.
 *
 * Setup required in Azure AD:
 * 1. App registration > Authentication > enable "Allow public client flows".
 * 2. API permissions must NOT require admin consent for the scopes you use,
 *    and the tenant must allow ROPC (some tenants block it via CA policy).
 * 3. The app registration must be a "public client" (no client secret used
 *    here, matching the public client flow — though ROPC can also be done
 *    confidential; this POC uses the public client variant).
 *
 * Reference: https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/entra/identity-platform/v2-oauth-ropc



===============================================================================================

* Requirement:

The Application (client) ID is a unique identifier assigned to your app when you register it in the Microsoft Entra admin center .

You can find this ID along with your Tenant ID on your app's Overview page within App registrations . Here is the exact path:

Sign in to the Microsoft Entra admin center .

Navigate to Identity > Applications > App registrations .

Select your application from the list .

On the Overview page, look for the Essentials section. There you will find both the Application (client) ID and the Directory (tenant) ID .

If you need to create a new app registration to get a Client ID, select New registration on the App registrations page, fill in the required details, and select Register. 
The Overview page will then display the new Client ID and Tenant ID .

=========================================================================================================================================

To test the OAuth 2.0 Resource Owner Password Credentials (ROPC) flow with Microsoft Entra ID,
you will need to prepare your test environment and then make a specific API request using the credentials you've obtained.

Here is a step-by-step guide to get everything you need and execute a test.

1. Prerequisites: 
* Create a Dedicated Test Tenant and User
It is crucial to use a separate test tenant for this, as Microsoft strongly recommends against using the ROPC flow in any production environment.

Create a Test Tenant: If you don't have one, create a new Microsoft Entra tenant for testing purposes. You can use the Microsoft 365 Developer Program or a free Azure account.

Create a Test User: In your new test tenant, create a dedicated test user account. Since this account won't be used by a real person, assign it a strong, complex password.

Important: This test user must not have multi-factor authentication (MFA) enforced. ROPC is incompatible with MFA, and the request will be blocked if MFA is required.


2. Configure a Test App Registration"

* You will also need an app registration specifically for your tests.

Register an App: In the Microsoft Entra admin center, navigate to App registrations and create a new application. Take note of the Application (client) ID that is assigned to it; you will need this for your API request.

Enable Public Client Flows: ROPC is a public client flow. In your app's registration, go to Authentication. Under Advanced settings, set Allow public client flows to Yes.

Configure API Permissions and Pre-consent: Go to API permissions and add the permissions your app needs for testing. 


3. The ROPC Token Request
With your test environment ready, you can now make a single POST request to the Microsoft identity platform token endpoint to get an access token.

Key Information Needed:

tenant: Your tenant ID or a domain name (like yourtesttenant.onmicrosoft.com). You cannot use the common or consumers endpoints; use your tenant-specific endpoint (https://login.microsoftonline.com/{TenantId_or_Name}) or organizations.

client_id: The Application (client) ID of your test app registration.

username: The username (UPN, usually an email address) of your test user.

password: The password of your test user.

Example  (HTTP):

Payload:
* 
POST https://login.microsoftonline.com/{tenant_id}/oauth2/v2.0/token
tenant:your_tenat_id
client_id: your_client-id
scope:user.read openid profile offline_access
username:yourusername@xyz.onmicrosoft.com
password: user account password
grant_type:password
client_secret: your client secret.

Parameters:

Parameter	Condition	Description
tenant	Required	Your directory tenant in GUID or domain name format. Cannot be common or consumers.
client_id	Required	The Application (client) ID assigned to your app.
grant_type	Required	Must be set to password.
username	Required	The user's email address (UPN).
password	Required	The user's password.
scope	Recommended	A space-separated list of permissions your app requires, which must be pre-consented.
4. Understanding the Response
Success: A successful request will return a JSON object containing an access_token, an id_token (if openid scope was requested), and an optional refresh_token (if offline_access scope was requested).

Example success response:

json
{
    "token_type": "Bearer",
    "scope": "User.Read profile openid email",
    "expires_in": 3599,
    "access_token": "eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsIng1dCI6Ik5HVEZ2ZEstZnl0aEV1Q...",
    "refresh_token": "AwABAAAAvPM1KaPlrEqdFSBzjqfTGAMxZGUTdM0t4B4...",
    "id_token": "eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJub25lIn0.eyJhdWQiOiIyZDRkMTFhMi1mODE0LTQ2YTctOD..."
}

Failure: Common errors include invalid_grant, which usually means the credentials were incorrect, the user has MFA enabled, or the app has not been consented for the requested scopes.

Security Warning: Microsoft strongly discourages using ROPC in production due to significant security risks and incompatibility with modern authentication features. It should be strictly limited to testing scenarios in a dedicated test environment. After a successful request, your application must securely discard the user's password from memory and never save it
